Mini project proposals


Project ideas - 

Mapping LIN28 binding sites at single nucleotide resolution using CLIP.
LIN28 is an RNA-binding protein highly expressed in pluripotent stem cells and certain types of cancer. It has two RNA-binding domain, a zinc-knuckle domain(ZKD)  and a cold shock domain (CSD). ZKD is known to bind a GGAG-like motif in RNA, including precursor let-7 microRNAs, but the binding specificity of the CSD was not determined for a long time. Ustianenko et al. (2018) examined the protein-RNA crosslink sites using LIN28 CLIP data generated by the ENCODE consortium and found a distinct RNA sequence motif. Repeat the analysis using CLIP Tool Kit (CTK), as described in the publication.  You are also highly encouraged to perform additional analysis to obtain any new biological insights.

Reference:
 Ustianenko, D., Chiu, H.-S., Treiber, T., Weyn-Vanhentenryck, S.M., Treiber, N., Meister, G., Sumazin, P. , Zhang, C.  2018. LIN28 selectively modulates a subclass of let-7 microRNAs. Mol. Cell. 71: 271-283.e5. 
 Feng, H., Bao, S., Rahman, M.,A., Weyn-Vanhentenryck, S.M., Khan, A., Wong, J., Shah, A., Flynn, E.D., Krainer, A.R., Zhang, C., 2019. Modeling RNA-binding protein specificity in vivo by precisely registering protein-RNA crosslink sites. Mol Cell. 74:1189-1204.E6.
Lectures/tutorials on Wednesday (8/13).


Resolving statistical debates on single-cell differential expression in memory-related gene expression analysis

Understanding how gene expression supports long-term memory formation remains a central challenge in neuroscience. A recent study by Sun et al. (Nature 2024) employed single-cell and spatial transcriptomics to reveal neuronâ€“astrocyte synergy in memory-related gene expression. However, Mukamel & Yu (Nature 2025) challenged the single-cell differential expression (DE) results reported in that work. They argued that all of the significant genes related to long-term memory identified in the original study were false positives, and the original analysis suffered from several fundamental statistical errors. In response, Sun et al. (Nature 2025) defended their original analytical approach in a reply article. Although the original paper and the two subsequent Matters Arising articles have all been published in Nature, the debate remains unresolved.

In this project, you are encouraged to conduct a comprehensive reanalysis focused on the single-cell DE findings in the original paper, with particular attention to statistical issues such as multiple-testing correction, the â€œdouble-dippingâ€ problem, and pseudobulk analysis. You are also encouraged to perform additional analyses aimed at uncovering new biological insights.

References:
Sun, W. et al. Spatial transcriptomics reveal neuronâ€“astrocyte synergy in long-term memory. Nature 627, 374â€“381 (2024) [https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-07011-6]
Mukamel, E. A. & Yu, Z. False positives in study of memory-related gene expression. Nature 642, E1â€“E3 (2025). [https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-025-08988-y]
Sun, W. et al. Reply to: False positives in study of memory-related gene expression. Nature 642, E4â€“E6 (2025). [https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-025-08989-x]
Pachter, L. Reply to: Reply to: False positives in the study of memory-related gene expression (2025) [https://liorpachter.wordpress.com/2025/06/16/reply-to-reply-to-false-positives-in-the-study-of-memory-related-gene-expression/]
